  "prompt": "Which is the best book for JEE maths?",
  "response": "Choosing the best book for JEE Mathematics depends on your current level of preparation, understanding, and the specific topics you want to focus on. Here are some highly recommended books that cater to different needs:\n\n### **For Concept Building and Fundamentals:**\n1. **\"Mathematics for Class 11 and 12\" by R.D. Sharma**  \n   - Excellent for building a strong foundation in JEE-level mathematics.  \n   - Covers all topics systematically with plenty of solved examples and exercises.  \n\n2. **\"NCERT Mathematics for Class 11 and 12\"**  \n   - Must-read for understanding basic concepts and theory.  \n   - Useful for both JEE Main and Advanced.  \n\n---\n\n### **For Advanced Problem Solving:**\n1. **\"Arihant's Problems in Mathematics\" by Vikas Gupta (Black Book)**  \n   - Focuses on advanced problem-solving techniques.  \n   - Contains a variety of challenging problems for JEE Advanced.  \n\n2. **\"Problems in Calculus of One Variable\" by I.A. Maron**  \n   - Highly recommended for mastering calculus concepts and problem-solving.  \n\n3. **\"Plane Trigonometry\" by S.L. Loney**  \n   - A classic book for trigonometry with in-depth explanations and problems.  \n\n---\n\n### **For Practice and Mock Tests:**\n1. **\"Previous Years' Solved Papers by Arihant\"**  \n   - Contains previous years' JEE Main and Advanced papers with detailed solutions.  \n\n2. **\"Skills in Mathematics\" series by Amit M. Agarwal (for JEE Main and Advanced)**  \n   - Topic-wise books with a focus on advanced problem-solving.  \n\n---\n\n### **Honourable Mentions:**\n1. **\"Higher Algebra\" by Hall and Knight**  \n   - Great for algebra concepts and problems.  \n\n2. **\"Coordinate Geometry\" by S.L. Loney**  \n   - Excellent for mastering coordinate geometry.  \n\n3. **\"Differential Calculus\" and \"Integral Calculus\" by Amit M. Agarwal**  \n   - Advanced books for JEE preparation, especially calculus.  \n\n---\n\n### **Tips:**\n- Start with NCERT and R.D. Sharma for basics.  \nLight and then move to advanced books like Arihant or Amit M. Agarwal.  \n- Solve previous years' papers to understand the exam pattern and difficulty level.  \n- Focus on quality over quantity\u2014mastering a few books is better than studying many superficially.  \n\nChoose the books based on your comfort level and thoroughness in each topic. Good luck with your JEE preparation! \ud83d\ude80",
  "temperature": 1.0,
